{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:42:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:42:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14890"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14890"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.11,0.08,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44610"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4521"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about exposure to chicken pox. She is 24 weeks pregnant and her three-year-old child was diagnosed with varicella infection two days ago. She is unsure if she has had chicken pox previously. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Urgent varicella serology reveals positive IgG and negative IgM.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No specific intervention required","Isolation from infected child","Acyclovir prophylaxis","Varicella zoster immunoglobulin administration","Urgent obstetric review"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a common clinical scenario where a pregnant woman is exposed to varicella (chicken pox) through contact with an infected child. The presence of positive varicella IgG antibodies indicates previous infection or vaccination, conferring immunity against reinfection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo specific intervention\u003C/strong\u003E is required in this case as the woman has documented immunity to varicella. The positive IgG indicates she has previously been infected with or vaccinated against varicella, providing long-lasting protection against reinfection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E administration would be indicated for non-immune pregnant women exposed to varicella. It should be given within 96 hours of exposure to prevent or attenuate infection. However, it is not necessary in immune individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsolation from infected child\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the mother is immune to varicella. Separation would cause unnecessary distress and disruption to the family unit without providing any medical benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcyclovir prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in immune individuals. It would be considered for treatment of active infection in high-risk individuals but is not needed for prophylaxis in immune pregnant women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent obstetric review\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as there is no risk to the pregnancy when the mother is immune to varicella. Routine antenatal care can continue as scheduled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary varicella infection during pregnancy can have serious consequences for both mother and fetus, including congenital varicella syndrome if infection occurs before 20 weeks gestation. However, these risks do not apply to immune mothers exposed to varicella.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Previous varicella infection confers long-lasting immunity and protects against reinfection during pregnancy.","Positive varicella IgG indicates immunity from previous infection or vaccination.","No specific precautions are needed for pregnant women with documented immunity who are exposed to varicella."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. East Melbourne: ASID; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 5]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44610"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14890"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44610"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T15:37:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T15:38:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7581"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59199"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta"